Url.Title: 5_StructuralPointConnection
Url.Abstract: StructuralPointConnection Node The basic object that specifies the geometry of the analytical model and its members. The nodes define other entity types. Each node is defined by position in modelling space and by its name. For example, a 1D member (StructuralCurveMember) is defined primarily by its two end-points that are nothing else but two nodes.

Url.Title: 7_StructuralCurveMember
Url.Abstract: StructuralCurveMember 1D Member (Beam, Column,…) A general 1D member is defined by its two end-points (or we can say nodes). Therefore, the 1D member position must be specified by two points: first, the starting or begin point then the end point and by a set of properties.

Url.Title: 8_StructuralSurfaceMember
Url.Abstract: StructuralSurfaceMember 2D member (Plate, Wall…) Instances of StructuralSurfaceMember describe face members, structural analysis idealizations of slabs, walls, shells. Surface members may be planar or curved with an arbitrary number of edges.

Url.Title: 9_StructuralSurfaceMemberOpening
Url.Abstract: StructuralSurfaceMemberOpening Opening in surface member Instances of StructuralSurfaceMemberOpening describe openings in planar members (StructuralSurfaceMember). The geometry of the opening object is defined in the same way as geometry of 2D members - may be planar or curved with an arbitrary number of edges.

Url.Title: 10_StructuralSurfaceMemberRegion
Url.Abstract: StructuralSurfaceMemberRegion The region of different plate thickness This object defines particular areas of the StructuralSurfaceMember with different thickness.

Url.Title: 11_StructuralPointSupport
Url.Abstract: StructuralPointSupport Support in node StructuralPointSupport is representing support of the analytical model in node. The support is defined by six separate parameters. Each parameter defines the constraint in one direction: translation in X, Y, Z axis and rotation around the same axes. A nodal support is oriented in global co-ordinate system.

Url.Title: 12_StructuralSurfaceConnection
Url.Abstract: StructuralSurfaceConnection Support on 2D member Instances of the objects StructuralSurfaceConnection are used to describe structural supports provided by planar elements. In most cases, it represents the interaction between the structure and the subsoil.

Url.Title: 13_StructuralEdgeConnection
Url.Abstract: StructuralEdgeConnection Supports on 2D members edges Object definition for a line support on a 2D member (StructuralSurfaceMember) edge. The support can be defined along the entire length of an edge or on its part only.

Url.Title: 14_RelConnectsStructuralMember
Url.Abstract: RelConnectsStructuralMember Hinges on 1D member The entity RelConnectsStructuralMember defines all needed properties describing the connection between structural members (beams, columns) and structural connection objects (nodes or supports). The connection may be rigid or free or anything in between. In each direction (translations along X, Y, and Z local 1D member axes, rotation around X, Y, and Z local 1D member axes) the condition may be: Free, Rigid, Flexible.

Url.Title: 15_RelConnectsSurfaceEdge
Url.Abstract: RelConnectsStructuralMember Hinges on 2D member edge A connection of two slabs (2D members) may be modelled as a fixed one or a hinge may be inserted to create a pinned connection. Three configurations of slab hinge are allowed: rigid, free, flexible. Under any configuration, all translations are fully transferred from one slab into the other.

Url.Title: 16_StructuralLoadGroup
Url.Abstract: StructuralLoadGroup Load group Load groups define "how the individual load cases may be combined together" if inserted into a load case combination. Thanks to the load groups, the user can easily specify which load cases MUST, MUST NOT, or CAN act together. Each load group may be used either for permanent loads or for variable loads. Permanent and variable loads cannot appear in the same group.

Url.Title: 17_StructuralLoadCase
Url.Abstract: StructuralLoadCase Load case Individual loads are not defined "freely". They must be included in load cases. A load case is a group, commonly used to group loads from the same action source. The load cases correspond with the professional terminology specified in national technical standards dealing with loads of civil engineering structures. The application of load cases follows the load management procedures that are usual and also obligatory in civil engineering practice.

Url.Title: 18_StructuralPointAction
Url.Abstract: StructuralPointAction Point force definition Instances of StructuralPointAction define a point load applied to the node (StructurePointConnection) and also the location of the point load on a 1D member (StructuralCurveMember).

Url.Title: 19_StructuralCurveAction
Url.Abstract: StructuralCurveAction Line force on the beam The Line force load models load distributed over a 1D member or on a slab edge. It may be action along the whole 1D member or only on its part. It can be constant or trapezoidal, acting in three main directions X, Y, Z (global or local coordinate system).

Url.Title: 20_StructuralSurfaceAction
Url.Abstract: StructuralSurfaceAction Surface load Defines actions on surfaces – plates, walls. The surface load is defined on the whole slab automatically. If only a part of the main slab is supposed to be subject to this load, a subregion (StructuralSurfaceMemberRegion) must be defined inside the main slab.

Url.Title: 21_StructuralPointMoment
Url.Abstract: StructuralPointMoment Moment force in node Specification in the excel:

Url.Title: 22_StructuralCurveActionFree
Url.Abstract: StructuralCurveActionFree Free line force The Free line load is related to slabs. The load is not defined by the entity it acts on, but by a specific load border. Free loads are defined by means of "loading entities" that may overlap or affect one or more slabs.

Url.Title: 23_StructuralSurfaceActionFree
Url.Abstract: StructuralSurfaceActionFree Free Surface load The Free line load is related to slabs. The load is not defined by the entity it acts on, but by a specific load border. Free loads are defined by means of "loading entities" that may overlap or affect one or more slabs.

Url.Title: Formcodes
Url.Abstract: Formcodes The shape of the cross-section is uniquely identified by a so called Formcode. The Formcode defines the shape, the parameters which describe the shape and in some cases also additional parameters like distance between bolt holes, unit warping ordinates etc.
